00:17:52,651 --> 00:17:56,954
You still have the exec producer who is managing the feature team, managing all the engineers,

224
00:17:57,014 --> 00:17:58,155
artists, designers, etc.

225
00:17:58,335 --> 00:18:02,758
And these guys are designing core gameplay features, major gameplay systems, and long-term

226
00:18:02,798 --> 00:18:03,018
things.

227
00:18:03,639 --> 00:18:11,503
Now the PM, once a game launches, generally becomes more hands-on and a lot of times elevates

228
00:18:11,563 --> 00:18:16,446
their stature in the game team to be an equal sort of business partner with the exec producer

229
00:18:16,846 --> 00:18:23,210
and will generally take control of a live team. So that team will work on live ops roadmap,

230
00:18:23,671 --> 00:18:28,353
they will continue to produce live content, oftentimes we'll staff it with analysts and

231
00:18:28,413 --> 00:18:31,375
we'll look at analytics and we will...

232
00:18:33,076 --> 00:18:45,026
We'll also look at how we can augment our live tools to create more nimble ways to interact with players and deliver content to players.

233
00:18:45,467 --> 00:18:51,371
So in a post-launch live service phase, a lot of times the PM, as I said, becomes more hands-on, becomes more prominent in the team,

234
00:18:51,992 --> 00:18:54,574
and a healthy team, as I see it, is one in which

235
00:18:55,050 --> 00:19:01,194
The exec producer and the PM are equal business partners and trust each other to make the right decisions.

236
00:19:01,714 --> 00:19:07,077
And, you know, the EP sort of trusts the PM as the sort of business voice behind the product,

237
00:19:07,458 --> 00:19:13,681
while the EP sort of takes center stage in town halls and summits, etc., to talk about the game.

238
00:19:13,701 --> 00:19:13,741
So.

239
00:19:17,804 --> 00:19:24,386
In AAA games, and because many AAA teams have spent years shipping games and then starting the next one,

240
00:19:25,186 --> 00:19:30,347
as we move into games as a service, the model in which you have to work sometimes is foreign,

241
00:19:30,547 --> 00:19:35,689
right? And as a result, integrating PMs into the team and adopting that iterative development

242
00:19:35,729 --> 00:19:40,830
mindset can sometimes prove challenging. And this is easier for some teams than others,

243
00:19:41,150 --> 00:19:44,771
but for those teams that have challenges, one of the purposes here is to talk about how to overcome this.

244
00:19:47,826 --> 00:19:51,728
So let's go into some common challenges and solutions, right?

245
00:19:52,508 --> 00:19:56,710
Of integrating, you've got PMs, you hired your first PM, right?

246
00:19:56,950 --> 00:19:58,551
He's really excited, he wants to contribute.

247
00:19:59,311 --> 00:20:01,172
But you're going to start to run into some challenges

248
00:20:02,192 --> 00:20:06,554
as a VP or GM, as an EP, whoever hired the PM,

249
00:20:06,894 --> 00:20:08,695
as you integrate these guys into your teams.

250
00:20:13,838 --> 00:20:15,758
Now the first sort of acceptance of the PM role.

251
00:20:16,350 --> 00:20:24,576
So as I said, PMs, game PMs who've had experience will come from other gaming companies, but a lot

252
00:20:24,596 --> 00:20:30,220
of times junior PMs will come from other backgrounds like consulting strategy, sometimes financial

253
00:20:30,260 --> 00:20:36,144
industry. And most non-mobile teams don't really understand the role of the PM in the development

254
00:20:36,184 --> 00:20:39,847
process. A lot of times because they have not worked in a live service product before, they

255
00:20:39,867 --> 00:20:45,571
have not worked in games as a service before, and they won't understand the PM's role. They won't

256
00:20:45,611 --> 00:20:45,791
know.

257
00:20:46,341 --> 00:20:48,282
how to interact with a PM initially.

258
00:20:49,903 --> 00:20:52,344
And as a PM, for those PMs in the audience,

259
00:20:52,624 --> 00:20:55,705
you have to accept the fact that in a AAA team,

260
00:20:55,725 --> 00:20:57,146
you'll often be viewed as the outsider.

261
00:20:57,406 --> 00:21:00,368
You'll often be viewed as sort of the black sheep.

262
00:21:00,688 --> 00:21:04,970
And that can have challenges to not only team onboarding,

263
00:21:05,570 --> 00:21:08,571
but also just team chemistry, morale, et cetera.

264
00:21:10,739 --> 00:21:13,120
And also just the value of the PM initially, right?

265
00:21:13,220 --> 00:21:16,140
If the PM is sort of viewed as someone that the team wants to

266
00:21:16,620 --> 00:21:17,801
sort of hide away in a corner

267
00:21:18,521 --> 00:21:20,942
and not have them be a prominent voice at the table,

268
00:21:21,242 --> 00:21:22,602
it will definitely limit their value.

269
00:21:23,502 --> 00:21:25,743
And a PM's value is directly correlated to

270
00:21:26,103 --> 00:21:28,123
the team's buy-in of the PM function.

271
00:21:29,184 --> 00:21:31,724
So this is something where early on,

272
00:21:31,964 --> 00:21:33,945
team acceptance of the PM role is going to be a challenge.

273
00:21:38,907 --> 00:21:52,753
The other thing, and I've learned this, teams, is that a lot of these teams, you know, maybe have worked on a live service before in a different way, right?

274
00:21:52,773 --> 00:21:59,156
Maybe they've worked on a game that shipped live DLCs, you know, or had post-launch content that they would launch.

275
00:22:00,097 --> 00:22:03,198
And because of this, they developed sort of pride in Ubis, right?

276
00:22:04,421 --> 00:22:11,850
And when you come in as PM, you'll say, I'm a PM, I look at business, I look at design and strategy, live execution, look at data, etc.

277
00:22:12,351 --> 00:22:17,197
Teams will often feel and they'll often say that they have the PM role covered by other functions.

278
00:22:20,867 --> 00:22:25,630
This is a little bit dangerous sometimes, but they'll say, you know, we've got live producers

279
00:22:25,670 --> 00:22:30,912
that produce our live content. We're good. We've got this. We have data analysts. We're working

280
00:22:30,932 --> 00:22:37,875
with the CI team and the data analysts. We're good. We got this. And, you know, it kind of

281
00:22:37,895 --> 00:22:39,196
stonewalls the PMs right away.

282
00:22:40,107 --> 00:22:42,328
And this is something that needs to be,

283
00:22:42,348 --> 00:22:44,168
need to look out for very closely.

284
00:22:44,908 --> 00:22:46,169
I would say for team leadership,

285
00:22:46,369 --> 00:22:48,069
as you onboard PMs onto your teams,

286
00:22:48,849 --> 00:22:50,129
because this is quickly something

287
00:22:50,149 --> 00:22:51,450
that could stonewall your PMs,

288
00:22:51,490 --> 00:22:52,970
can demotivate them, et cetera.

289
00:22:53,590 --> 00:22:57,591
If your team doesn't know how to interact

290
00:22:58,011 --> 00:22:59,852
and does feel that they have the PM role covered

291
00:22:59,872 --> 00:23:00,592
by other functions.

292
00:23:01,392 --> 00:23:03,232
You know, sometimes it's the case that they do,

293
00:23:04,012 --> 00:23:06,073
but most oftentimes it's the case

294
00:23:06,473 --> 00:23:07,493
that they actually don't.

295
00:23:09,253 --> 00:23:12,675
And you know, they're standing there, I can hear, and the house is burning down.

296
00:23:12,955 --> 00:23:15,637
So this is something that you have to be mindful of.

297
00:23:19,800 --> 00:23:23,863
So how do you circumvent these challenges? And there are ways to do it.

298
00:23:25,464 --> 00:23:31,328
One of the things that PMs can do, and I like to think of this as a bottoms-up approach versus

299
00:23:31,388 --> 00:23:36,872
a top-down approach, one approach is always the GM or the VP saying, these are your PMs,

300
00:23:38,219 --> 00:23:43,121
Listen to them. They do X, Y, and Z, and you need to rely on them for this. That's definitely a top-down way.

301
00:23:43,421 --> 00:23:48,343
If you're a PM, I would approach this as a bottom-up way. And one way is to involve the

302
00:23:48,383 --> 00:23:53,384
dev team in PM processes. And this is something that we've seen a great deal of success with

303
00:23:54,225 --> 00:24:01,127
on products over my career. So FIFA Online is one example where we instituted the feature impact

304
00:24:01,147 --> 00:24:06,369
assessment process. It was a process that we set up to instill rigor in

305
00:24:07,947 --> 00:24:11,008
You know, shipping our client releases and the types of releases we're shipping,

306
00:24:11,809 --> 00:24:15,371
looking at the KPI impact of the of the releases we're shipping.

307
00:24:15,911 --> 00:24:19,654
And the rest of the team was fully involved and we made sure to do it this way.

308
00:24:20,614 --> 00:24:24,016
We set up different milestones for these feature impact assessments

309
00:24:24,156 --> 00:24:28,959
that integrated into the development process each milestone.

310
00:24:29,299 --> 00:24:32,301
So at the beginning of a milestone, we would come in and look at the design docs

311
00:24:32,341 --> 00:24:32,721
with the team.

312
00:24:33,407 --> 00:24:38,128
We would get a full sort of download of what the feature was trying to achieve,

313
00:24:38,528 --> 00:24:42,809
and then we would come with our KPIs and say, what do we think this is going to be?

314
00:24:43,010 --> 00:24:45,070
It would be a brainstorming process for the team.

315
00:24:45,090 --> 00:24:49,852
It's going to do engagement, it's going to up monetization, and by how much, right?

316
00:24:50,552 --> 00:24:55,053
And then after the feature was released, and after we had sufficient data, we would come back

317
00:24:55,593 --> 00:24:59,835
and we would task the analytics team with pulling all the right data, we would put it together,

318
00:24:59,855 --> 00:25:01,255
and we would do

319
00:25:02,310 --> 00:25:09,333
a postmortem of okay how did this feature actually perform versus what we expected.

320
00:25:09,913 --> 00:25:14,315
And so for FIFA mobile in China we've extended this to a weekly program analysis

321
00:25:15,056 --> 00:25:20,158
because you know a lot of our live content is in the form of programs and it's it's a faster

322
00:25:20,198 --> 00:25:25,160
content cadence because it's mobile. So we have this weekly program analysis with the dev team

323
00:25:25,540 --> 00:25:31,302
to understand the why behind different decisions. So feature impact assessment

324
00:25:32,481 --> 00:25:34,382
program impact assessment, et cetera,

325
00:25:35,082 --> 00:25:36,123
and doing it at a regular cadence

326
00:25:36,483 --> 00:25:38,644
and doing it in the same timeline

327
00:25:39,265 --> 00:25:41,106
and integrated into the milestone

328
00:25:41,126 --> 00:25:42,567
that the process of the team

329
00:25:43,287 --> 00:25:44,948
and involving the team early on.

330
00:25:45,708 --> 00:25:49,170
So they can get exposure to you as a PM

331
00:25:49,991 --> 00:25:52,332
and they can see the value that you bring early on

332
00:25:52,412 --> 00:25:54,293
in discussions to get to alignment.

333
00:25:54,713 --> 00:25:56,854
And then later on, once we get the data

334
00:25:57,195 --> 00:25:59,556
and showing what impact these features actually have.

335
00:25:59,935 --> 00:26:02,597
So that was a very positive way for us to do it.

336
00:26:04,618 --> 00:26:10,781
Another thing that I've implored all my PMs across different games to do,

337
00:26:11,361 --> 00:26:17,184
it's something that other teams like the Pentium team, which I'm very closely in communication

338
00:26:17,224 --> 00:26:23,227
with them, does as well, is to work for the team rather than trying to lead.

339
00:26:23,927 --> 00:26:29,270
And there's a lot of literature on the PM function out there, a lot of it related to other tech.

340
00:26:30,073 --> 00:26:36,217
Parts of the tech industry that sometimes I view as erroneous and damaging a bit in gaming is that

341
00:26:36,517 --> 00:26:43,762
a lot of times PMs are paraded around as the CEO of the product and you've got these eager PMs that

342
00:26:43,822 --> 00:26:51,768
come in and they try to lead right away. Oftentimes this is the wrong approach. As I said, you need

343
00:26:51,788 --> 00:26:55,210
to accept the fact that you're going to be viewed as an outsider when you come into these teams.

344
00:26:55,290 --> 00:26:58,953
One great way to build equity is to work for the team rather than trying to lead.

345
00:27:00,092 --> 00:27:03,573
And one of the things that we've done, you know, across the products that I'm across,

346
00:27:03,633 --> 00:27:09,934
across other products that other heads of PM are across at EA, is to embed PMs directly in the dev

347
00:27:09,954 --> 00:27:15,636
team and require them to split time between sitting with a centralized PM pod and sitting

348
00:27:15,656 --> 00:27:20,017
with the core team. Oftentimes we'll just have our PMs sit directly with the core team.

349
00:27:20,563 --> 00:27:25,927
um all the time and you know you wouldn't think this is important where they sit but it's extremely

350
00:27:25,967 --> 00:27:31,531
important um to sit with the team and then we'll come back to the pm pod maybe one day a week or

351
00:27:31,591 --> 00:27:38,075
just during our scrums etc um but you know all pms will sit with the team and they'll begin

352
00:27:38,536 --> 00:27:39,496
onboarding onto the team

353
00:27:39,937 --> 00:27:45,602
by basically listening to team needs, talking to team leadership, and tailoring their tasks to

354
00:27:46,003 --> 00:27:51,928
the team needs. And this is something that I've observed is that, you know, for different projects

355
00:27:51,948 --> 00:27:55,872
our PMs, the needs of the PM are going to be different.

356
00:27:57,602 --> 00:28:03,226
Sometimes you've got a team with designers that are very quantitatively motivated and you may need

357
00:28:03,246 --> 00:28:09,250
to do less hand-holding with the design team onboarding with analytics. Sometimes you'll

358
00:28:09,270 --> 00:28:14,834
have to do more, right? Sometimes it just depends on how the project shakes out, but because PM

359
00:28:14,854 --> 00:28:22,980
skills are so cross-functional and so broad-based, PMs can often tailor their tasks and tailor their

360
00:28:23,020 --> 00:28:25,022
function to the team needs and should be doing.

361
00:28:25,600 --> 00:28:31,182
So this is something that we've seen a lot of success with at EA, both on products that I'm

362
00:28:31,222 --> 00:28:36,804
across and products that are other heads of PM across the company and in EA Mobile and, you know,

363
00:28:36,864 --> 00:28:43,306
Max and BioWare Maxis also have had success with. He is working for the team rather than trying to,

364
00:28:43,326 --> 00:28:45,026
you know, take the lead right away.

365
00:28:49,127 --> 00:28:54,809
Another thing beyond team acceptance of the PM role is ownership and accountability, right?

366
00:28:55,530 --> 00:29:01,132
And this is something that AAA teams are very, you know, they'll harp about this a lot.

367
00:29:01,992 --> 00:29:07,354
I've noticed more, more so than mobile teams, is what are you actually accountable for? What

368
00:29:07,394 --> 00:29:13,536
are you actually owning? And one harsh reality is that because, again, the PM role is very

369
00:29:13,576 --> 00:29:18,678
cross-functional, there will be confusion about what PMs own and are accountable for.

370
00:29:20,287 --> 00:29:21,948
And you see this sort of, you know,

371
00:29:23,749 --> 00:29:25,789
the cameo from Office Space here,

372
00:29:25,809 --> 00:29:26,910
if any of you have seen that,

373
00:29:27,070 --> 00:29:29,050
and one of my favorite scenes in the movie.

374
00:29:30,371 --> 00:29:32,372
But you'll actually get these questions

375
00:29:33,012 --> 00:29:34,312
from people on your dev team.

376
00:29:34,733 --> 00:29:36,513
A guy from QA will come up and say,

377
00:29:37,053 --> 00:29:39,434
what are you actually doing here?

378
00:29:39,514 --> 00:29:41,735
Or a designer or creative director will say,

379
00:29:42,155 --> 00:29:43,095
what value are you adding?

380
00:29:44,056 --> 00:29:46,117
And a lot of times, you know,

381
00:29:47,059 --> 00:29:52,624
It's on you to educate, but it also can be damaging to the morale of new PMs.

382
00:29:53,645 --> 00:30:01,072
Being met with this type of attitude, I guess, from people on the team that they're actually excited to be a part of.

383
00:30:01,152 --> 00:30:05,456
But it's a harsh reality that you'll have to accept that there will be confusion.

384
00:30:05,836 --> 00:30:08,298
And there are definitely ways to solve that confusion.

385
00:30:10,020 --> 00:30:11,982
So, how do we solve for this?

386
00:30:14,025 --> 00:30:17,026
One of the things I've learned in my years as a PM leader is that

387
00:30:18,607 --> 00:30:22,509
the strike team approach is a very popular sort of approach to PMing where

388
00:30:22,529 --> 00:30:26,610
you'll have PMs in a central pod who will,

389
00:30:27,090 --> 00:30:30,091
you know, whenever a project has problems, whenever a game

390
00:30:30,271 --> 00:30:33,232
isn't hitting their KPIs, they'll come in as a strike team

391
00:30:33,613 --> 00:30:37,174
or they'll move from project to project. And this is something that I've learned

392
00:30:37,234 --> 00:30:38,875
is actually better off abandoning.

393
00:30:43,942 --> 00:30:48,624
Because as a strike team approach, PMs come in as consultants, they come in as advisors,

394
00:30:49,245 --> 00:30:54,107
and then they roll off. So not only does the team not always understand what they're doing,

395
00:30:54,227 --> 00:31:00,331
what they're accountable for, but they're gone from the project six months later or a year later,

396
00:31:00,511 --> 00:31:04,573
and were they actually part of the team? So abandoning this approach and actually making

397
00:31:04,593 --> 00:31:09,356
them part of the team is, I think, a really good thing to do. So in FIFA,

398
00:31:09,983 --> 00:31:15,785
One of the things that was done very early was we bifurcated the team into dev and live, right?

399
00:31:16,665 --> 00:31:23,328
So as I said before, the feature team and the live content team. And early on, the PM team

400
00:31:23,548 --> 00:31:28,789
actually assumed direct ownership of the live content team and the live roadmap, eliminating

401
00:31:28,849 --> 00:31:33,591
ambiguity as to what they are responsible for. If someone says, what do you do? What are you

402
00:31:33,651 --> 00:31:34,191
accountable for?

403
00:31:34,992 --> 00:31:37,033
I control, I'm the decision maker for the live team.

404
00:31:37,353 --> 00:31:38,854
That's a very short answer.

405
00:31:38,874 --> 00:31:42,076
And it was one that we had a lot of success with.

406
00:31:43,797 --> 00:31:48,540
FIFA Mobile in China was a project that launched very fast and very aggressively,

407
00:31:49,060 --> 00:31:50,841
but it quickly sort of bottomed out.

408
00:31:51,341 --> 00:31:54,164
And once we did this sort of bifurcation of the team,

409
00:31:55,305 --> 00:31:57,147
and gave PMs control of the live team,

410
00:31:58,488 --> 00:32:00,750
our performance started coming up considerably.

411
00:32:01,170 --> 00:32:03,833
We nearly doubled our DAU,

412
00:32:04,013 --> 00:32:07,196
and we've been on a very good sort of trajectory ever since.

413
00:32:07,256 --> 00:32:09,658
So it's something from a performance standpoint that worked,

414
00:32:09,918 --> 00:32:12,220
and it's something from a sort of...

415
00:32:12,583 --> 00:32:17,726
Team function standpoint worked because the team was able to gel, was able to work very quickly

416
00:32:17,786 --> 00:32:23,150
without, you know, sort of scratching their head as to, you know, what does the PM actually own here.

417
00:32:23,910 --> 00:32:28,974
In the BioWare team with Anthem, I think I talked about with, you know, we had a senior leader

418
00:32:29,534 --> 00:32:35,898
that was hired now a couple years ago in BioWare, who's a great guy, hired for that PM function

419
00:32:36,018 --> 00:32:39,040
reporting directly to, you know, the VP GM of that studio.

420
00:32:41,913 --> 00:32:47,176
and had his PMs assume accountability for the live roadmap in a similar way.

421
00:32:47,636 --> 00:32:53,879
So one part of that was having a leader come in to sort of represent the PM function in BioWare

422
00:32:54,760 --> 00:32:59,863
for Anthem and another one was to have other PMs come in accountability over things like

423
00:33:00,503 --> 00:33:06,746
game economy and live roadmap and other things that the team quickly saw had massive value

424
00:33:08,067 --> 00:33:09,488
as you know Anthem was seen.

425
00:33:09,807 --> 00:33:12,221
At that point, a game is a service and live service product.

426
00:33:16,185 --> 00:33:21,669
Another way to sort of, you know, circumvent this harsh reality I was talking about before

427
00:33:21,689 --> 00:33:27,975
is to use sign-off. And the reason you use sign-off is it forges dependencies within the team, right?

428
00:33:28,515 --> 00:33:35,001
And this is something that a lot of times the GM or the VP will have to do as a top-down thing,

429
00:33:35,681 --> 00:33:38,564
but it's very powerful once it's done. And this is something that we've done

430
00:33:38,884 --> 00:33:43,328
across our FIFA products, our free-to-play FIFA products in Asia.

431
00:33:44,448 --> 00:33:46,350
with FIFA Mobile and FIFA Online.

432
00:33:47,170 --> 00:33:48,711
Even though these products were both free to play,

433
00:33:49,292 --> 00:33:54,496
the teams working on them were not mobile teams.

434
00:33:55,256 --> 00:33:57,998
These were teams that came from AAA, so that's why I'm including them here.

435
00:33:59,159 --> 00:34:03,202
But we quickly had this sign-off built in where

436
00:34:03,982 --> 00:34:06,464
we aligned in our interop site that PMs would own

437
00:34:06,804 --> 00:34:09,306
all engagement metrics for the game.

438
00:34:11,344 --> 00:34:14,226
Also design the model used for forecasting and operational modeling

439
00:34:14,426 --> 00:34:17,428
and how we basically lock financial forecasts and financial targets.

440
00:34:17,468 --> 00:34:20,210
So because financial targets have to be locked every month,

