00:36:57,522 --> 00:37:00,043
So, harsh reality, how do we get around that?

482
00:37:02,437 --> 00:37:08,960
One way to get around, I think, I feel, is to use frameworks to maintain rigor in fact-based decision making.

483
00:37:09,280 --> 00:37:16,944
Now, this is something where, you know, the Anthem team, again, had a really good way to do this.

484
00:37:17,704 --> 00:37:21,686
And this is something that I actually barred for them, and it's worked very well for me, too.

485
00:37:22,906 --> 00:37:24,787
It is speaking in frameworks, right?

486
00:37:25,536 --> 00:37:31,021
Maybe we don't all agree on what the right decision is. Maybe we don't want to talk about

487
00:37:31,382 --> 00:37:36,606
retention that's lower than we thought it would be or revenue that's lower. But can we all agree

488
00:37:37,143 --> 00:37:45,645
That as a team we all have the same shared goals. Can we all agree that our goal is to maximize

489
00:37:45,665 --> 00:37:52,666
traffic and to maximize revenue? It's to grow MAU as much as possible. It's to grow our monthly

490
00:37:52,706 --> 00:37:58,588
revenue as much as possible. And oftentimes when you get down to that very simple fact-based

491
00:37:58,708 --> 00:38:04,389
decision making and that simple framework, those goals are irrefutable for the rest of the dev team.

492
00:38:04,690 --> 00:38:07,412
I don't think anyone's going to tell you no, we want to minimize traffic.

493
00:38:08,653 --> 00:38:12,916
So you break it down into first principles and you establish those shared goals.

494
00:38:13,476 --> 00:38:18,340
And once you've aligned on those shared goals, what you realize is that magic starts to happen,

495
00:38:18,560 --> 00:38:18,780
right?

496
00:38:19,620 --> 00:38:24,344
Once you can agree on those shared goals, you can move to the brainstorming phase about

497
00:38:24,524 --> 00:38:28,587
what the best ways are to get there instead of arguing over the goals themselves.

498
00:38:29,027 --> 00:38:29,227
So

499
00:38:30,018 --> 00:38:34,960
Now that we know that MAU is, you know, something that we want to maximize, how do we do that?

500
00:38:35,200 --> 00:38:40,362
And then that's where PMs start to shine, because PMs can bring proposals for how to maximize MAU.

501
00:38:40,983 --> 00:38:45,524
And a lot of times in our meetings with teams where we bring in those plans,

502
00:38:45,725 --> 00:38:48,746
the team's response is, oh, we'd never thought about it that way.

503
00:38:49,166 --> 00:38:49,226
Oh.

504
00:38:50,104 --> 00:38:51,145
Yeah, that's actually true.

505
00:38:51,706 --> 00:38:53,448
That's not something that's top of mind for us.

506
00:38:53,948 --> 00:38:56,011
And they start to realize the value

507
00:38:56,051 --> 00:38:58,714
of the different perspective of data-driven reality

508
00:38:58,794 --> 00:39:00,776
that PMs will bring into the team

509
00:39:01,337 --> 00:39:02,498
when they're thinking about things

510
00:39:02,598 --> 00:39:03,519
in a little bit different way.

511
00:39:04,702 --> 00:39:10,126
So this is something that I would highly recommend is speaking in frameworks and using frameworks

512
00:39:10,186 --> 00:39:12,627
to maintain rigor in fact-based decision making.

513
00:39:13,308 --> 00:39:18,151
I think I feel is something I think everyone eventually sort of reverts to, but it's something

514
00:39:18,171 --> 00:39:21,274
that has to be kept in check on a more regular basis.

515
00:39:23,855 --> 00:39:25,276
Another way to win is...

516
00:39:26,105 --> 00:39:29,466
Again, to use business realities to pressure test decisions, right?

517
00:39:30,067 --> 00:39:34,709
So sometimes the team will, you know, make a feature decision or make a design decision

518
00:39:34,809 --> 00:39:40,312
based on, I think, I feel, and that client release will get shipped and, you know,

519
00:39:40,652 --> 00:39:44,053
the PM will have said or someone on the team will have said, yeah, I don't think we should

520
00:39:44,073 --> 00:39:47,755
be doing this because X, Y, Z, and the team should have said anyway.

521
00:39:48,155 --> 00:39:53,218
However, if you have the right processes set up, you can pressure test those decisions.

522
00:39:53,458 --> 00:39:53,598
So...

523
00:39:55,184 --> 00:39:58,726
On all our products now, we have bi-weekly business reviews.

524
00:39:58,966 --> 00:40:00,668
Every two weeks, we have a business review,

525
00:40:00,688 --> 00:40:03,250
which are high visibility, comprehensive reviews

526
00:40:03,290 --> 00:40:05,391
of the business, the live ops performance,

527
00:40:05,512 --> 00:40:06,873
and how we're tracking versus targets.

528
00:40:06,913 --> 00:40:07,913
And this is very simple.

529
00:40:07,933 --> 00:40:10,936
This is something that I think a lot of teams

530
00:40:11,056 --> 00:40:12,897
that are listening to this probably already do

531
00:40:13,118 --> 00:40:16,180
in some shape or form, but I would encourage these

532
00:40:16,300 --> 00:40:20,103
to include a lot of cross-functional people in the team,

533
00:40:20,623 --> 00:40:24,586
not just the PMs and the producers, but across the team.

534
00:40:25,130 --> 00:40:31,614
And I would actually encourage you to include execs in these reviews to the extent that you can.

535
00:40:31,734 --> 00:40:35,536
Because when you do that, and when you have execs present,

536
00:40:35,676 --> 00:40:39,378
when you execs will want to talk about objective things, right?

537
00:40:39,538 --> 00:40:42,379
It makes it hard to hide in the gray area, I think, I feel.

538
00:40:43,340 --> 00:40:48,104
And very quickly, it starts to change the team's mindset in terms of what's important,

539
00:40:48,404 --> 00:40:52,868
and in terms of who needs to be consulted before decisions get made.

540
00:40:52,968 --> 00:40:58,793
And that can have some very powerful sort of impact in terms of how the team approaches releases,

541
00:40:59,294 --> 00:41:01,916
how the team approaches live content development, etc.

542
00:41:02,276 --> 00:41:05,399
And I think we've seen that prove out across our products.

543
00:41:05,539 --> 00:41:11,424
FIFA Mobile I'm using as an example here, which is where we've seen a profound impact.

544
00:41:12,156 --> 00:41:17,661
But we've seen the same impact on FIFA Online, we've seen the same impact on Red Alert, and

545
00:41:17,701 --> 00:41:19,303
it's something that I would highly recommend.

546
00:41:26,618 --> 00:41:31,840
is on the org structure side is maintaining an unbiased view through central reporting lines

547
00:41:32,360 --> 00:41:35,800
but at the same time staying embedded within the core team and sit together.

548
00:41:36,040 --> 00:41:39,181
Right, I go back to sitting together because I think it's really important.

549
00:41:40,381 --> 00:41:46,222
So it's a fine balance, right? A lot of times, you know, the PM function is well-staffed on a lot

550
00:41:46,242 --> 00:41:51,483
of teams. A lot of times you'll see PMs reporting into the exec producers of these different games.

551
00:41:52,344 --> 00:41:56,228
which can work in some cases, but can also be dangerous in others.

552
00:41:56,789 --> 00:42:03,757
And the reason it can be dangerous is because the PM, you know, as a great communicator of data and business realities,

553
00:42:04,117 --> 00:42:11,445
can sometimes become a tool to mask business realities or sort of, you know,

554
00:42:11,966 --> 00:42:18,389
Use data to basically communicate whatever message the exec producer or the creative director wants to put forth

555
00:42:18,689 --> 00:42:23,252
versus the actual sort of unbiased truth. So for that reason,

556
00:42:24,233 --> 00:42:28,895
especially in orgs where the PM function is not that sure yet,

557
00:42:29,135 --> 00:42:31,997
I recommend a central reporting line structure.

558
00:42:32,717 --> 00:42:34,118
So a structure more like this

559
00:42:34,758 --> 00:42:37,020
where you have a director of product

560
00:42:38,481 --> 00:42:41,162
that reports into a VP or GM or other exec.

561
00:42:41,818 --> 00:42:46,799
That person has PMs under him, and those PMs are embedded within the team.

562
00:42:47,119 --> 00:42:51,681
They sit with the team, they tailor their tasks to the team's needs,

563
00:42:52,161 --> 00:42:54,282
and they dotted line into the team leadership.

564
00:42:54,542 --> 00:42:59,343
However, they report back into the head of product, who reports back into the GM,

565
00:43:00,123 --> 00:43:04,365
which serves as a nice sort of check and balance on the team in terms of, as I said again,

566
00:43:04,805 --> 00:43:09,992
I think I feel over data-driven realities, right? And it sort of keeps that in balance. And I think

567
00:43:10,452 --> 00:43:15,359
one of the reasons why these bi-weekly reviews have been so strong for us, why feature impact

568
00:43:15,379 --> 00:43:20,626
and these other sort of central processes have been so strong, is because of this matrix-based

569
00:43:20,666 --> 00:43:21,047
reporting.

570
00:43:22,168 --> 00:43:28,673
That said, I think on teams where PMs have sat there for years, where you have EPs who are very

571
00:43:28,733 --> 00:43:33,537
fast and agile and have worked on several games as a service or free-to-play games before,

572
00:43:34,217 --> 00:43:39,441
this structure can work. I'm not saying it can't work, but when you're introducing the

